{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c050503e-aff8-4615-951a-16cc07baceaa","content":"Your project isn't present in this workspace, but here's how to configure it. Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your project root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout, which is the standard for local MCP servers.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout**. Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n\nIf you've already published a self-contained executable instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the binary:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the **Copilot Chat** panel in agent mode and your server's tools should appear automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc890a4b-409e-4db1-97f3-4539f5236b6e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist, but the user is asking for configuration guidance, not for me to build the project. I can still answer their question about how to configure `mcp.json`.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"D033:2A7C5F:14E092C:17604F3:6A0673EE"},"id":"f74b609c-16ef-4692-9f4c-439c33e2abd7","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:16:39.912Z","parentId":"5e981130-dfc1-481b-8017-fdf8e6803431"}
